WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:04.735
[SPEAKER_01]: I will endeavor our efforts and our contribution to the world.

00:05.456 --> 00:11.802
[SPEAKER_05]: This is the first time in our city's history that City Hall is lit up in the lights and colors of the Korean flag.

00:12.022 --> 00:21.551
[SPEAKER_05]: It signifies the fact that the Korean American community is valued and that we matter and that we're part of the larger fabric and family of Los Angeles.

00:22.833 --> 00:29.599
[SPEAKER_60]: We know that Los Angeles is for everyone and it's important to celebrate each other and that's what we're doing right now.

00:34.000 --> 00:40.389
[SPEAKER_13]: Preparing for college is an intimidating process, made a little easier by the Los Angeles Public Library.

00:40.810 --> 00:48.240
[SPEAKER_13]: Their workshop at the Chinatown Branch broke down the application process, highlighted what to expect, and featured a local success story.

00:55.090 --> 01:00.177
[SPEAKER_63]: So today we're here at the Chinatown Branch Library for a Get Ready for College program.

01:01.507 --> 01:18.115
[SPEAKER_29]: We are here today to talk about the college admission process at the Chinatown Public Library as one of the assistant directors of admission and also as someone who's from Chinatown, I think it's a great honor to be able to come here, talk to the students, give a little bit more insight about it and also share my story as well.

01:18.095 --> 01:38.905
[SPEAKER_34]: I showed up to the college workshop today because I am a rising junior and I wanted to know more about the college process and how to be you know get a better chance to getting like some colleges like UC's that you know are closer to me.

01:38.885 --> 01:42.589
[SPEAKER_16]: Going through college is a hard, long process.

01:43.090 --> 01:45.713
[SPEAKER_16]: Basically, you need to read all the applications yourself.

01:45.753 --> 01:51.380
[SPEAKER_16]: You need to decide whether you want to go to a big school, a small population, what curriculum.

01:51.901 --> 02:02.073
[SPEAKER_16]: So today is more for, instead of you diving through by yourself, there are people here just to walk you through, to guide you through, to give you pointers on where to go to find out more information on what you need.

02:02.193 --> 02:04.656
[SPEAKER_29]: Focus on writing about yourself and your own story.

02:04.636 --> 02:07.521
[SPEAKER_29]: So the difference between college and high school is a lot.

02:07.541 --> 02:10.767
[SPEAKER_29]: I think applying to college you realize that there's a lot.

02:10.787 --> 02:16.036
[SPEAKER_29]: There's ways to kind of pursue your career for the long run and also it's a very different environment.

02:16.056 --> 02:17.639
[SPEAKER_29]: You meet folks from all over the world.

02:18.581 --> 02:20.224
[SPEAKER_29]: You are also learning about yourself.

02:20.244 --> 02:21.366
[SPEAKER_29]: You're living on your own.

02:21.847 --> 02:28.298
[SPEAKER_29]: So I think there's a big difference in terms of just kind of figuring out your purpose and you're also in an environment to do so.

02:28.278 --> 02:37.729
[SPEAKER_34]: I think it's really important right now to get this information since there's so much you know misinformation about college.

02:38.049 --> 02:52.345
[SPEAKER_29]: I hope after this event that students are able to kind of feel less intimidated by the college application process so I hope I was able to give them the confidence to apply and also ask questions and share their story with us.

02:54.772 --> 02:57.441
[SPEAKER_13]: providing a cleaner environment in South LA.

02:57.682 --> 03:07.093
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilmember Curran Price celebrated more green spaces and links between the area's parks, rolling out an expansion of the Greenway Network in South LA.

03:09.470 --> 03:14.235
[SPEAKER_33]: Today we're going to be announcing expansion of the CD9 Greenway Network.

03:15.417 --> 03:28.030
[SPEAKER_33]: We're excited to be here today to celebrate the importance of open space, green space, rededicating the commitment CD9 has to creating a livable environment for kids, for seniors, for all.

03:28.311 --> 03:33.216
[SPEAKER_33]: Initially our Greenway encompassed Slauson from Normandy to Compton Boulevard.

03:33.196 --> 03:38.890
[SPEAKER_33]: We also quickly incorporated Avalon, because along Avalon, we have three parks and a bikeway.

03:38.910 --> 03:42.479
[SPEAKER_33]: And last week, we inaugurated a greenway along MLK.

03:42.639 --> 03:47.030
[SPEAKER_33]: And so we've got an interesting network, a greenway network in City and I.

03:47.250 --> 03:48.573
[SPEAKER_33]: And today, we're going to be celebrating that.

03:48.694 --> 03:51.340
[SPEAKER_33]: We're kicking it off this morning, and then we're going to take a bike ride.

03:54.475 --> 04:13.530
[SPEAKER_07]: That green corridor, which is the one we just walked through now, filled me with joy because I saw the whole community, children, adults, adults, happy and just waiting for more events like this to come because the community needs it so much and we are very happy and grateful.

04:13.510 --> 04:37.290
[SPEAKER_00]: I really like it and I do see a lot of the community coming out and it makes me happy and proud that we have a place to come and gather where people can exercise and live a healthy life.

04:38.013 --> 04:45.025
[SPEAKER_45]: Some would say that District 9 is a concrete jungle, but what I see what the Councilman is doing, he's opening up green spaces.

04:45.246 --> 04:53.220
[SPEAKER_45]: It's just wonderful to be able to walk into a community where you can have some peace, some quiet, and just think and meditate.

04:53.892 --> 04:57.377
[SPEAKER_07]: The council has done all this for us, for our community.

04:57.397 --> 05:07.951
[SPEAKER_07]: That is his legacy and the truth is that I saw my daughter grow up here and now I see how she enjoys the parks and all the benefits and all the good things she has done for us.

05:08.031 --> 05:13.999
[SPEAKER_07]: So that is also a call for the community to come and see the green areas where they are.

05:14.600 --> 05:21.790
[SPEAKER_07]: It helps the environment and also, as I repeat, it helps you healthily, mentally and also your body.

05:25.803 --> 05:32.362
[SPEAKER_33]: Folks need to be able to enjoy their environment safely, and the environment needs to be conducive for that.

05:32.483 --> 05:40.065
[SPEAKER_33]: So we encourage open space, green space, and folks to walk, to bike, and to enjoy the outdoors.

05:46.880 --> 05:50.330
[SPEAKER_13]: $4.5 million of stolen cargo is recovered.

05:50.912 --> 05:57.912
[SPEAKER_13]: San Fernando Gardens gets climate resilient and there's a new general manager at the city's El Pueblo Historical Monument.

05:58.433 --> 06:00.720
[SPEAKER_13]: These stories up next on City Beat.

06:07.096 --> 06:18.271
[SPEAKER_52]: The Los Angeles Police Department's Commercial Crimes Division announced the seizure of $4.5 million in stolen property and the arrest of a key individual for retail and cargo theft.

06:18.771 --> 06:30.927
[SPEAKER_52]: LAPD worked with LA Port Police and Union Pacific Police to recover tools, appliances, e-bikes and other items, which were being fenced through a storefront and online platform.

06:30.907 --> 06:40.846
[SPEAKER_52]: According to LAPD Chief Jim McDonald, protecting the integrity of the supply chain is vital to public safety as well as the economic stability of Los Angeles.

06:41.427 --> 06:49.301
[SPEAKER_52]: Anyone with information on retail or cargo crime is urged to contact Crimestoppers, where tips can be reported anonymously.

06:49.782 --> 06:53.910
[SPEAKER_52]: For more information, visit LAPDOnline.org.

06:56.253 --> 07:04.032
[SPEAKER_52]: L.A. City Housing Authority, HACLA, was joined by Congresswoman Rivas to tour new energy-efficient upgrades at San Fernando Gardens.

07:04.754 --> 07:13.536
[SPEAKER_52]: Federal funds of $3.5 million are being used to bring more sustainable and resilient living conditions to nearly 1,500 residents.

07:13.516 --> 07:22.664
[SPEAKER_52]: HACLA is installing 448 energy-efficient air conditioning units donated by the Office of Mayor Bass and the L.A. Department of Water and Power.

07:23.284 --> 07:33.033
[SPEAKER_52]: The community center at San Fernando Gardens has also been upgraded to serve as a resiliency center with backup solar power energy in case of a heat emergency.

07:33.733 --> 07:43.101
[SPEAKER_52]: According to HACLA, extreme weather adversely impacts the San Fernando Valley, and these enhancements will improve the quality of life for public housing residents.

07:43.081 --> 07:45.804
[SPEAKER_52]: For more information, visit hackla.org.

07:48.587 --> 07:56.917
[SPEAKER_52]: LA City Council has confirmed Dominica Lynch as the new general manager of El Pueblo Historical Monument and its first Latina leader.

07:56.937 --> 08:07.890
[SPEAKER_52]: A graduate of the University of Southern California, Lynch has more than 20 years' experience in nonprofit organizations supporting Latino and other underrepresented communities.

08:07.870 --> 08:18.004
[SPEAKER_52]: According to Mayor Bass, El Pueblo's leader needs to preserve its history and activate business and event space, especially during this challenging time for immigrant communities.

08:18.745 --> 08:22.310
[SPEAKER_52]: Lynch will begin as general manager of El Pueblo on October 20th.

08:22.871 --> 08:27.938
[SPEAKER_52]: For more information, visit mayor.lacity.gov slash press.

08:35.275 --> 08:42.367
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilwoman Heather Hutt celebrated with community members as the city designated the home of Tom Bradley, a historical monument.

08:42.968 --> 08:49.960
[SPEAKER_13]: This was just one of a series of African American landmarks being honored, adding to the rich cultural tapestry of Los Angeles.

08:52.910 --> 08:54.091
[SPEAKER_60]: It's so exciting.

08:54.111 --> 08:56.193
[SPEAKER_60]: We're at the home of Tom Bradley.

08:56.394 --> 09:02.520
[SPEAKER_60]: He was a mayor for 20 years in Los Angeles and he was the council member right here in the 10th district first.

09:02.961 --> 09:08.967
[SPEAKER_60]: We're in Lamar Park and what we've done is designated his home as a historical monument.

09:09.347 --> 09:21.280
[SPEAKER_60]: His children are here and they've been able to talk about their experience growing up in a community that wasn't really as multicultural as it is today.

09:21.260 --> 09:28.500
[SPEAKER_60]: And then coming from that, we're going to St. Elmo's Village to talk about youth's contributions to this city.

09:28.941 --> 09:36.602
[SPEAKER_60]: And then we're moving to Catch One, which was Jules Tyus Williams' big club for LGBTQ community.

09:39.316 --> 09:49.296
[SPEAKER_47]: The African American Historic Places LA project is a joint project between the City of Los Angeles' Office of Historic Resources and the Getty Conservation Institute.

09:49.316 --> 09:57.072
[SPEAKER_47]: So some of these sites that we are designating are not architecturally significant or have an architecturally high style, so you could miss them.

09:57.389 --> 10:07.984
[SPEAKER_47]: St. Omo Village is an artist enclave, a set of 10 bungalows that were created by Roderick and Rozelle Sykes because they were shunned from the art world.

10:08.164 --> 10:12.991
[SPEAKER_47]: They couldn't get their paintings sold in mainstream white art institutions.

10:13.412 --> 10:16.596
[SPEAKER_47]: And they also wanted an opportunity for anybody.

10:16.576 --> 10:19.299
[SPEAKER_47]: people of color, anybody to have access to art.

10:19.640 --> 10:26.148
[SPEAKER_47]: And then Catch One, sadly, we lost Jules, who is the owner and creator of Catch One.

10:26.409 --> 10:31.095
[SPEAKER_47]: And she opened the first black gay disco in the United States.

10:31.515 --> 10:35.660
[SPEAKER_47]: And that was also during a time where folks were still ostracized.

10:35.981 --> 10:38.644
[SPEAKER_47]: So that club became a haven for everyone.

10:39.185 --> 10:45.553
[SPEAKER_47]: It's a symbol of hope for the LGBTQ plus community now, and it still operates as a dance club.

10:47.120 --> 10:54.788
[SPEAKER_47]: So if you walk down the Tom and Ethel Bradley residence and that plaque wasn't there or the signage wasn't there, you would think that it was an ordinary home.

10:54.848 --> 10:57.271
[SPEAKER_47]: It is an ordinary home, but it has an extraordinary story.

10:59.273 --> 11:06.621
[SPEAKER_47]: He and his family bought this house at a time where there were restrictive covenants, where non-whites couldn't live in the community.

11:06.922 --> 11:11.727
[SPEAKER_47]: So they broke barriers, not only broke barriers in the community, but broke barriers in the police force.

11:13.107 --> 11:14.950
[SPEAKER_58]: My sister and family moved here.

11:14.990 --> 11:23.745
[SPEAKER_58]: My parents, brave as they were to make that move in 1950 to come to this area where we were not appreciated, where we were actually hated.

11:24.266 --> 11:28.753
[SPEAKER_59]: Riding down the street and seeing all the neighbors come out waving and

11:28.733 --> 11:29.474
[SPEAKER_59]: I was afraid.

11:29.915 --> 11:32.319
[SPEAKER_59]: Like my mother said, she didn't know what she was driving up into.

11:32.639 --> 11:37.046
[SPEAKER_58]: Took the neighbors a long time to come to the realization that we were just like them.

11:37.667 --> 11:44.818
[SPEAKER_58]: And because of it, there's a whole generation out there that are benefiting from the courage that mom and dad had.

11:48.005 --> 11:52.876
[SPEAKER_60]: So we're just showing what historical locations we have in the 10th district.

11:53.177 --> 12:03.921
[SPEAKER_60]: It's a very exciting day, especially for folks that have worked hard to commemorate these spaces at a time where so much of our history is trying to be erased.

12:11.680 --> 12:18.661
[SPEAKER_13]: Summer fun at the pool is a chance to try out all the activities that LA City's Department of Recreation and Parks has to offer.

12:19.143 --> 12:23.496
[SPEAKER_13]: Time to swim by the Westwood Rec Center and dive into their pool party.

12:26.024 --> 12:31.892
[SPEAKER_27]: So today we're at the Westwood Rec Center and today we're doing the pool party that we host annually every summer.

12:32.613 --> 12:48.994
[SPEAKER_27]: We're working with Council District 5 and we're here to support the West LA community and basically what we do, we introduce them to our learn to swim programs, our small craft programs and today we have a fortunate opportunity to introduce our Wibbit that they're utilizing and they're having a blast.

12:51.100 --> 12:57.135
[SPEAKER_27]: We have a small craft program where we introduce learn to surf, learn to paddle, and then we also do learn to kayak.

12:57.416 --> 13:04.755
[SPEAKER_27]: So, you know, giving the community members an opportunity to see those that they don't normally see and it gets them more prepped for open bodies of water.

13:07.486 --> 13:10.750
[SPEAKER_19]: My kids have loved coming to the Westwood Pool.

13:11.310 --> 13:17.197
[SPEAKER_19]: My older one has been doing swim team, she did Camp Splash, and the littler one is taking little lessons here and now.

13:17.257 --> 13:19.440
[SPEAKER_19]: This place is like home, we love it.

13:20.321 --> 13:24.426
[SPEAKER_19]: They love the slide, that giant inflatable slide.

13:24.666 --> 13:26.088
[SPEAKER_19]: They went on it five or six times.

13:27.750 --> 13:34.978
[SPEAKER_19]: And then they enjoyed the food, of course, and I think they're going back in right now to go back on that slide, but maybe they'll do some paddle boarding too.

13:38.738 --> 13:40.525
[SPEAKER_10]: This is a fun park.

13:40.545 --> 13:41.910
[SPEAKER_10]: I love it.

13:41.930 --> 13:43.877
[SPEAKER_10]: And it also has a nice swimming pool.

13:43.897 --> 13:49.197
[SPEAKER_10]: It's a lovely water jungle, didn't I call it?

13:49.217 --> 13:49.639
[SPEAKER_10]: It's really fun.

13:49.659 --> 13:49.980
[SPEAKER_10]: I love it.

14:04.220 --> 14:06.885
[SPEAKER_27]: So all of our pool parties are free to the community.

14:07.266 --> 14:10.872
[SPEAKER_27]: You know, we want to get as many people introduced to our aquatic facilities.

14:10.972 --> 14:23.275
[SPEAKER_27]: We want everybody to know that they have a pool in their neighborhood and we want them to feel supported and we want them to be introduced to a lot of our programs to make them feel safe and mainly to educate them on water safety.

14:33.700 --> 14:37.330
[SPEAKER_13]: Sex trafficking of minors is taking place in parts of Los Angeles.

14:37.752 --> 14:43.267
[SPEAKER_13]: LA City Attorney Heidi Feldstein Soto has made disrupting the demand her top priority.

14:43.809 --> 14:48.081
[SPEAKER_13]: She highlights a number of tactics being brought to bear on those committing these crimes.

14:53.326 --> 15:04.279
[SPEAKER_51]: I came into this office and I was surprised at what I found in terms of how human beings treat our young people and our kids.

15:08.824 --> 15:18.355
[SPEAKER_51]: And my first project in collaboration with Mayor Bass and Councilmember Marquise Harris-Dawson was focused on the sex trafficking of minors.

15:20.360 --> 15:28.309
[SPEAKER_51]: Protecting our children and sort of finding ways to stop the exploitation and abuse of our kids has been one of my top priorities.

15:33.675 --> 15:39.042
[SPEAKER_51]: I focused on what's known as the kiddie stroll, K-I-D-D-I-E, about little children.

15:39.762 --> 15:44.528
[SPEAKER_51]: And these are kids who are taken out and paraded on the street for sex.

15:48.760 --> 15:55.154
[SPEAKER_51]: In the Figueroa Street Initiative, we have rescued over 200 minor children, the youngest of whom was 12.

15:55.756 --> 16:00.526
[SPEAKER_51]: And we've provided, delivered them into the hands of service providers and helped them get off the streets.

16:01.328 --> 16:04.896
[SPEAKER_51]: We've also focused on shutting down the motels.

16:04.876 --> 16:09.505
[SPEAKER_51]: that are crime magnets and who don't bring themselves into compliance with applicable law.

16:10.386 --> 16:19.303
[SPEAKER_51]: And on arresting felons, predators, Kimps, we've referred, I think, 74 cases to the U.S. attorney or the D.A.'

16:19.283 --> 16:21.687
[SPEAKER_51]: 's office for prosecution.

16:21.667 --> 16:27.780
[SPEAKER_51]: And probably one of my favorite things that I learned in the course of this initiative is we send out Dear John letters.

16:28.441 --> 16:36.759
[SPEAKER_51]: So part of our effort is to disrupt the demand from the adult men who were there to purchase sex from a young child.

16:37.541 --> 16:38.663
[SPEAKER_51]: And we

16:38.643 --> 16:48.933
[SPEAKER_51]: have surveillance cameras, we get a picture or photograph of the automobile with the license plate and of the man basically doing the transaction for sexual services.

16:49.534 --> 16:58.543
[SPEAKER_51]: And we send the photograph and a letter to the registered owner of the vehicle saying, dear registered owner, your car has been seen in an area known for human trafficking of minors.

16:58.883 --> 17:02.387
[SPEAKER_51]: Please be aware we're conducting operations in the area and be more careful.

17:03.248 --> 17:05.730
[SPEAKER_51]: The registered owner is usually the spouse.

17:07.752 --> 17:20.833
[SPEAKER_51]: And we're going to stop the illegal street walking trafficking of our kids on Figueroa and on what's known as the Sepulveda track in the valley for the parents of children.

17:22.062 --> 17:26.529
[SPEAKER_51]: where the parents think there may have been abused, please report it to the LAPD.

17:27.170 --> 17:33.700
[SPEAKER_51]: They have officers trained in working with very young victims, and they will get it into the right hands.

17:34.080 --> 17:40.129
[SPEAKER_51]: If you're undocumented and you're not comfortable reporting it to the LAPD, my office has a helpline.

17:40.770 --> 17:45.117
[SPEAKER_51]: We have a program that's dedicated to children exposed to violence.

17:45.097 --> 17:48.922
[SPEAKER_51]: I note that I am the first female city attorney.

17:49.282 --> 17:51.645
[SPEAKER_51]: I'm the first Latina elected citywide.

17:52.206 --> 17:56.651
[SPEAKER_51]: And so many of our young victims are black and brown girls.

17:57.212 --> 18:10.007
[SPEAKER_51]: From my perspective, there is no higher calling to a prosecutor than protecting the vulnerable, than being sure that justice prevails.

18:09.987 --> 18:20.241
[SPEAKER_51]: And when you're talking about little kids, they don't have their own voice without help from their families and without help from prosecutors like me.

18:20.261 --> 18:35.522
[SPEAKER_51]: And so from day one in the office, really sending out a message that abuse of children and specifically sexual abuse of children will not be tolerated, not in the city of L.A. and not by the city attorney.

18:41.645 --> 18:46.234
[SPEAKER_13]: A face-to-face community space that exposes arts and music to all.

18:46.876 --> 18:55.553
[SPEAKER_13]: At the William Grand Still Arts Center, people can be themselves and become part of a greater collective, reflecting the community and supporting local artists.

19:27.005 --> 19:51.139
[SPEAKER_02]: The mission behind the William Grestel Arts Center is one that is based in art and music exposure to the community, very intergenerational in our programming that includes yearly exhibitions, there's concerts, film screening, workshops, after school classes, all into sharing about art and music in the community.

19:52.385 --> 20:00.577
[SPEAKER_11]: You learn from everyone, whether that be the Black Doll Show, the African American Composer Series, working with youth as well.

20:00.597 --> 20:09.550
[SPEAKER_11]: So we're constantly learning from each other and I think that's something really beautiful about the center and what space it creates for the community.

20:14.120 --> 20:34.356
[SPEAKER_25]: One of the great things about our community art center is that we allow the community to be themselves as they are, using the language and vernacular that's local, using the codes and cues that are local, but also tapping into a greater discourse that's national and international.

20:34.336 --> 20:48.177
[SPEAKER_02]: The programming that is offered and the way that it is offered, it can foster relationships, but also just having a face-to-face space to come to, to convene, to find solace.

20:49.299 --> 20:50.961
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, it's important.

20:52.679 --> 20:58.405
[SPEAKER_11]: I really admire this center and have much love for the center for the space it creates.

20:58.926 --> 21:06.334
[SPEAKER_11]: Having a physical space that offers things that are tangible, you're able to connect with others.

21:08.396 --> 21:19.868
[SPEAKER_25]: So one of the things that's really important about a community arts facility, it is actually owned by the people of Los Angeles, meaning that the people of Los Angeles know and get exactly what they want.

21:20.118 --> 21:21.581
[SPEAKER_25]: It's an added resource.

21:22.062 --> 21:25.029
[SPEAKER_25]: It's exhibitions that feature local artists.

21:25.049 --> 21:26.633
[SPEAKER_25]: So we want to continue this.

21:26.773 --> 21:27.956
[SPEAKER_25]: We want to foster this.

21:28.156 --> 21:36.675
[SPEAKER_25]: LA has been the place that a lot of artists have come out of and it will continue to be as long as we support community facilities like these.

21:44.536 --> 21:49.324
[SPEAKER_13]: In this week's Things to Do, Los Angeles Libros Festival celebrates much more than books.

21:49.825 --> 21:57.177
[SPEAKER_13]: Go arm-in-arm to the Festival of Philippine Arts and Culture and join the City of LA for El Grito 2025.

21:57.638 --> 21:59.862
[SPEAKER_13]: All this up next on Things to Do.

22:06.473 --> 22:13.921
[SPEAKER_52]: The Los Angeles Public Library invites you to read, dream, and celebrate with them for the Los Angeles Libros Festival.

22:14.602 --> 22:20.248
[SPEAKER_52]: Now in its seventh year, the Libros Festival is a free bilingual book festival for the whole family.

22:20.929 --> 22:29.798
[SPEAKER_52]: The celebration creates an inclusive cultural space to engage and inspire current and future generations of bilingual Angelenos.

22:29.778 --> 22:41.034
[SPEAKER_52]: With 16 authors appearing during the day, there'll be entertainment and fun with Spanish language and bilingual storytelling, musical performances, workshops, readings, and community.

22:41.534 --> 22:55.093
[SPEAKER_52]: Head to Downtown's Central Library for the Los Angeles Libros Festival on Saturday, September 13th, from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. For more information, visit lapl.org slash Libros.

22:57.402 --> 23:03.950
[SPEAKER_52]: Join LA City's Department of Cultural Affairs and Phil M. Arts for the Festival of Philippine Arts and Culture.

23:03.990 --> 23:11.398
[SPEAKER_52]: This year's theme is Arm in Arm, reflecting unity, resilience, and the vibrant spirit of the Filipino-American community.

23:11.979 --> 23:20.068
[SPEAKER_52]: On Saturday, September 13th, come to Point Furman Park for the music, stay for the food, and enjoy the company of fellow festival goers.

23:20.048 --> 23:29.582
[SPEAKER_52]: There'll be music and dance performances that bridge tradition and innovation on two stages, along with vendors, a first ever dog fashion show, and more.

23:30.163 --> 23:43.963
[SPEAKER_52]: The 31st year of the Festival of Philippine Arts and Culture is on Saturday, September 13th, beginning at 10 a.m. and continuing until 6 p.m. For more information, visit philamarts-fpac.org.

23:46.087 --> 23:54.455
[SPEAKER_52]: Join the city of Los Angeles to celebrate El Grito, also known as the Cry of Dolores, taking place on Saturday, September 13th.

23:55.036 --> 24:06.567
[SPEAKER_52]: This year, it's the turn of council member Eunice Hernandez to host El Grito 2025, which will include a bell ringing on the steps of City Hall, followed by music performances into the night.

24:07.087 --> 24:15.435
